{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17628429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17628429"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:56:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17219"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17219"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74835"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17219"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60341"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"9022"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23243"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74835","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74835"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a severe, throbbing headache that is frontotemporal in location. She reports visual loss, jaw pain and lethargy. On further examination, she is found to have ophthalmoplegia. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Giant cell arteritis","Neoplasm","Hypertensive crisis","Meningitis","Low cerebrospinal fluid pressure headache"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003EGiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as temporal arteritis. The combination of a severe, throbbing headache, visual loss, and ophthalmoplegia is characteristic of this condition. Giant cell arteritis is an inflammatory disease of blood vessels, most commonly involving the large and medium arteries of the head. It can lead to ischemic complications, including visual loss and cranial nerve palsies, due to reduced blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eneoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially cause similar symptoms if it were to compress cranial nerves or the optic pathway, but the acute presentation and the combination of symptoms are more typical of giant cell arteritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypertensive crisis\u003C/strong\u003E can cause headache and visual disturbances, but it is less likely to cause ophthalmoplegia and mononeuropathies without other systemic signs of severe hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with headache, fever, neck stiffness, and altered mental status. While it can cause cranial nerve palsies, the absence of systemic symptoms makes it less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elow cerebrospinal fluid pressure headache\u003C/strong\u003E is usually positional and associated with a history of recent lumbar puncture or trauma. It does not typically cause visual loss or ophthalmoplegia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Giant cell arteritis can present with headache, visual loss, and ophthalmoplegia.","Mononeuropathies can occur in giant cell arteritis due to ischemic damage to nerves.","Prompt recognition and treatment of giant cell arteritis is crucial to prevent permanent vision loss."],"references":["Bigal ME, Lipton RB. The differential diagnosis of chronic daily headaches: an algorithm-based approach. J Headache Pain. 2007 Oct;8(5):263-72. doi: 10.1007/s10194-007-0418-3. Epub 2007 Oct 23. PMID: 17955166; PMCID: PMC2793374","Ahmed F. Headache disorders: differentiating and managing the common subtypes. Br J Pain. 2012 Aug;6(3):124-32. doi: 10.1177/2049463712459691. PMID: 26516483; PMCID: PMC4590146","Lee AW, Chen C, Cugati S. Temporal arteritis. Neurol Clin Pract. 2014 Apr;4(2):106-113. doi: 10.1212/CPJ.0b013e3182a9c62a. PMID: 29443189; PMCID: PMC5765614.","Ameer MA, Vaqar S, Khazaeni B. Giant Cell Arteritis (Temporal Arteritis) [Updated 2024 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459376/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60341"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17219"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60341"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-27T16:32:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T18:57:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9909"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74835"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"